@node "Require" "NetBar and NetView Requirements"

To run either NetBar or NetView you must have Gui4Cli v2.2 installed
on your system see @{"Introduction" link "Intro" 0} for where to get it.

@{b}Requirements:@{ub}

             @{b}OS 2.04@{ub} or above
             @{b}Gui4Cli v2.2@{ub} (installed before NetBar)
             ASL.library (in LIBS:)
             Hard Drive (if floppy only have fun)
             times.font (standard Amiga one)               
             AmigaGuide (in c:)
             8 colour workbench (it will look kak if lower)

To make full use of these programs you will need some helper programs
(lha etc) outlined in the @{"Helpers" link "helpers" 0} section.

@{b}Notes:@{ub}

             To make NetBar look the way it should click the ClickMe icon
             to set the correct palette then start Palette Prefs to alter
             and SAVE it the way you like it. (please do not remove any of
             the greys)

             DO NOT run in 4 colours or you won't read the buttons as they
             will come out black and you will have to play with your palette.
            (8 colours or more)

@endnode

@node "overview" "Overview of NetBar"

                              @{b}  NetBar@{ub}
                             @{b} **********@{ub}

@{b}Buttons:@{ub}

 There are five picture/text buttons and one cycling text button.  
 Each time you press the cycling button the title will change from 
 Log On to Log Off and visa versa. The cycling button is for the logon
 and hangup scripts, so the first time you press it it will logon and
 the next time you press it it will hangup.

 The other buttons will launch your Net apps like any button bar.
 There are also two menu items for net apps Ping and Telnet.
 Remember they only launch what you have set them to launch, so if
 you dont have an IRC or Telnet client you could set them to launch
 AmiSlate or Finger or what ever, but the titles of the menu items 
 stay the same. The buttons are actually icons (look in the icons drawer)
 and can be edited like a normal icon (icon edit won't work as the icons
 are to wide) but be careful not to cock them up. (make a copy first)

@{b}Menus:@{ub}

 Like WorkBench if you press your right mouse button while NetBar is
 active you can access NetBars menus as listed below.

@{b}Help:@{ub}

      @{b} Help NetBar:@{ub}
            This will bring this guide up so you can have easy
            access to all the helpy type bits (good aye).

      @{b} About NetBar:@{ub}
            This will just bring up the NetBar about window (boring).
            You must have AmigaGuide in c: to launch it from NetBar.

@{b}Extras:@{ub}

       @{b}Ping:@{ub}
            This will launch what ever you set in Net Apps     

       @{b}Telnet:@{ub}
            Same as above
    
@{b}Tools:@{ub}

      @{b} AutoView:@{ub}
            This will bring up a standard ASL requester so you can
            choose an archive or picture file to extract or view etc.
            When you have chosen your file AutoView will try to guess
            the filetype and launch the correct extractor/viewer, but
            if it cannot guess correctly it will give you the choice
            to launch NetView where you can pick from a list of common
            filetypes dependant on the @{"helpers" link "helpers" 0} you have installed on your
            system. Please read the section on @{"NetView" link "netview" 0} for more info.
       
      @{b} AutoIcon:@{ub}
            This wil place an AppIcon on your WorkBench where you can just
            drag and drop files and it will be the same as picking a file
            with AutoView (without the ASL requester) see AutoView above.
            When NetBar exits the icon will go too.

      @{b} Pakit:@{ub}
            This will bring up a little gui where you can lha and or
            uuencode/base64 files for sending on the Net etc.
            See @{"Pakit" link "pakit" 0} for more info. 

@{b}Settings:@{ub}

      @{b} Net Apps:@{ub}
            This will bring up a gui where you can enter the paths for
            your Net clients (web browser, news reader etc) for the 
            corresponding buttons on NetBar. You can either type in the
            locations to your apps or press the corresponding "get"
            button to bring up an ASL requester where you browse around
            for them.

            If you need to place any command line options for your apps
            (i.e. AmiTCP:ping -c10 194.192.193.1) just type them into the
            text window after you have selected.
            Once you have all your apps setup the way you want click save
            to return to NetBar.
            
       @{b} Misc:@{ub}
            This will bring up a gui where you can enter the paths for 
            your logon and hangup scripts as well as your the drawer where
            you want AutoView or NetView to extract your archives to.
            If you dont pick a UnArc drawer it will default T: (normally
            Ram:T on most Amigas). If you plan to extract large archives
            dont use ram as you may run low on memory for other apps.

            @{b}PLEASE TRY NOT TO@{ub} bury your apps in sub-directorys after 
            sub-directorys or make directory names to long as they wont fit
            in the text window or charactor buffer. 

i.e. not:- work:AmiTCP/comms/more_comms/even_more_comms/oh_look_more_comms/
                                                   are_here_it_is/Aweb/Aweb

i.e. more like this:- work:AmiTCP/Aweb/Aweb

            Also do not use names with spaces in (i.e. ram disk) as they
            will be quoted by AmigaDos (i.e. "ram disk:") and will play havok
            with some progs. If you must use ram disk: select it then in the
            text box change ram disk: to ram: it will still work the same.

i.e. ram disk:downloads becomes ram:downloads (easy aye)               

@{b}Quit:@{ub}
     Well what can I say it will exit NetBar (and remove Gui4Cli from memory
     if no other guis are loaded).
     

@endnode


@node "pakit" "Pakit compressor/encoder"

Pakit is just a simple gui where you can prepare files for uploading to
the Net.

Here you can compress using lha (the Aminet standard) and encode using
either Mime/Base64 or UU encoding.

It's very easy to use. First you choose file (files if lha etc) you want
to work on in the top text window using the Get button, then select the
destination drawer in the bottom text window. Once you have the desired
drawer selected type in the name you want for the out-file:-

example:

  In the requester select a drawer say Work:test/ (don't click any files)
  Then in the file section type myfile (no extension)
  Thats it now click the button for the method you wish to use.       

If you want to compress (lha only) all the files in a drawer don't select
any files leaving the file section blank and all files will be compressed.
This can save time instead of selecting the files one by one, but if the 
drawer has sub-directorys as well they will also be compressed.
So if you only wish to compress the files and not the sub-directorys you
will still have to select each file in the drawer.

Multi file selection is acheived by holding down the Shift button while
clicking on each file you want. DO NOT use multiple files with either
mime or uu it won't work. (see important notes below)

With Mime/UU encoding you can pick either LHA-MIME or LHA-UU and this will
lha the file(s) then when all is done encode the finished file appending
.bin for mime or .uue for uuencoded at the end.

i.e.
myfile will become myfile.lha then myfile.uue or .bin containing myfile.lha

It is best to use the above method as uu/mime encoding normally makes a 
file bigger than it was in the first place as it must convert binary to 
text. (this includes text files)

Only use lha compression if sending to another Amiga user and not for Usenet
news groups etc as PC and Mac users will be relying on .zip even though they
can get an lha extractor for their format but are to lazy. 

(Ah Sod erm let them eat lha he he he !!)

Lha is set to recurse sub-drawers (if any) so say you have a drawer called
"pics" containing two more called "gifs" and "jpegs" you would go to pics
(using the requester) and type #? in the bit where the filename would be and
lha will compress the lot.

@{b}IMPORTNAT NOTES@{ub}
@{b}***************@{ub}

Multiple files can only be used with lha as Mime and UU can only work on 
a single file so you must use lha first.

Mime/UU encoding will only make one whole file as I can't be bothered to
include file spliting routines so get a better ISP if you want to send 
large files and yours restricts your file sizes. ("Mine don't")

@endnode


@node "helpers" "Helper programs"

Helpers is just a silly name for external programs such as lha, ppshow etc.

The more helpers you have installed the more NetBar and NetView can achieve
for you and make your Net sessions easier.

Without any helpers you can forget about using AutoView or NetView except
for viewing the contents i.e. text etc (as reader built in).

You don't have to have all the helpers below just the ones you wish to use
all that will happen is the corresponding buttons won't do anything as check
to see if you have them installed before trying to run them.

All helpers must be in your c: drawer (WorkBench:c)

Most of these programs can be found on numerous cover disks/cds and are all
on Aminet.

@{b}Helpers:-@{ub}

@{i}Achivers:@{ui}

@{b}lha@{ub}    for .lha/.lzh files (Aminet standard)    (aminet/util/arc/lhA_e138.run)

@{b}lzx@{ub}    for .lzx files                           (aminet/util/arc/lzx120.lha)

@{b}unarj@{ub}  for MSDOS .arj files (not that common)   (aminet/util/arc/UnARJ241.lha)

@{b}unzip@{ub}  for MSDOS .zip files                     (aminet/util/arc/unzip51x.lha)

@{b}untgz@{ub}  for UNIX .tar.gz .tgz files              (aminet/util/arc/Untgz.lha)

@{b}base64decode/encode@{ub}  for Mime/Base64 files      (aminet/util/arc/base64coders.lha)

@{b}uuhx@{ub}   for UUencoded files (usenet files)       (aminet/util/arc/uuhx.lha)


@{i}Viewers/players:@{ui}

@{b}AmigaGuide@{ub} for guide files (standard with WorkBench)

@{b}ppmore@{ub}  for PowerPacked text files (not important)          

@{b}play16@{ub}  for iff wav vox and more sound files    (aminet/mus/play/play16_1_4.lha)

@{b}ppshow@{ub}  for anim jpeg gif iff picture files     (aminet/gfx/show/??)

@{b}mp@{ub} (mpegplay) wait for it .mpeg .mpg files      (aminet/gfx/show/mp103.lha)

@{b}xanim@{ub}  for .fli .flc .avi .mov(QT) files        (aminet/gfx/show/xanim8.lha)

It's best to pop into the relevant directories on Aminet to get these files
as I am not 100% certain of their names.

@{b}MultiView@{ub}  (OS 3.x) and loads of datatypes for various filetypes
(i.e. wave, sunaudio, bmp, png, tiff etc)

Please read the enclosed docs for each helper you get for requirements
and system specs as some require more memory and higher cpu's.

An 020, OS 3.x and 4mb fast ram is recommended by most progs. Any lower and the 
Internet is a real drag and once your web browser etc are loaded it don't leave much.

An A1200 with 4mb fast ram is perfect. (std A500 users etc hard luck)


@endnode


@node "netview" "NetView file manipulator"

NetView is a stand alone gui in its own right as well as part of NetBar
and can be used when NetBar is not loaded, so you can use it in your
everyday computing. 

NetView will only uncompress or view files it will not compress them if
you wish to compress files choose @{"Pakit" link "pakit" 0} from the menu.

When you launch NetView from inside NetBar your chosen file will be
displayed in the text box below. If you start NetView from its own icon
you must select a file from the File - Open menu (or click the open button)
which will bring up an ASL requester where you can find your file.

NetView has loads of buttons showing filetypes and options just press 
the corresponding button for the filetype you have selected and NetView
will run the corresponding @{"Helper" link "helpers" 0}.

If all goes well your archive will be extracted or pic/doc etc will be
shown etc.

If you can't work out what type of file it is choose "View contents" and
a text viewer (which will read binaries) will load it up where you can 
look for clues. Once you have worked out what it is dont have to go back
to NetView just select the helper from the menu and run it from there.
Please don't try to view the contents of massive movie file (i.e. avi's 
and mpeg's etc) as you may find your out of memory very quick.

If you keep Contents Viewer open but make it smaller you can drag and drop
files into it as it is an AppWindow and the files will be loaded as if you
had picked them with a requester.

If you have OS 3.x or above you can choose multiview and dependant on the
datatypes you have installed view all types of files.

If the file is a program there is a button called "what the hell run it" 
which will try to run the file form NetView. Please don't use this unless
your like me and keep everything backed up and like fixing computers as 
you may crash the hell out of your system and lose everything.

If you plan to use NetView and have not setup or don't want to use NetBar
you will have to set the path for your unarchiving drawer from the Settings
UnArc Dir menu.

Please read the section for setting your paths in the @{"overview" link "overview" 0} of NetBar
before going any further with NetView.

NetView has a few little buttons at the top, these are NetViews toolbar.

From left to right:

The 1st button is "Open" and will bring up a requester where you can pick a
file to work on.

The 2nd button is "New" and will start Pakit. (see @{"Pakit" link "pakit" 0}

The last button is "help" and will load this guide file. 

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Once you have picked your button and the file is loaded/run etc NetView will
sometimes close to free chip memory and clear the screen of clutter, sorry but
I only intended this for use with NetBar and can't stand loads of little windows
etc cluttering up my screen. ("So call me names see if I care")


@endnode


@node "gui4cli" "What is Gui4Cli"

Below are some exerts from the Gui4Cli.guide to get you exited so you will
get it and run my prog, and hopefuly make some of your own.

                           *** Gui4Cli ***
               An interpretive GUI programming language
                      (c) 1996 by D.C.Keletsekis

Gui4Cli is an interpretive programming language for the easy creation of
GUIs. It provides Gadgets, Menus, Appitems etc, through an easy script-like
language, allowing you to construct resizable font-sensitive GUIs and through
them, control other programs by issuing CLI and ARexx commands.

A Graphical User Interface (GUI), is the Buttons, Cyclers, Sliders,
Menus and all the other gadgets you play with when using a program.

Gui4Cli is a program which enables anyone to write such a GUI and
from it, issue CLI or ARexx commands to other programs.

What you do, is write a script in the Gui4Cli programming language,
(which is very easy) and just run it!

@{b}How it works:@{ub}
--------------

Gui4Cli is and Event-Driven language. This means that it reacts to
various events, such as the clicking of a gadget by the user, or
a command to close the window etc.

Events can be Gadgets, Menus, AppMenuItems, User Actions etc.

A GUI program is a series of such events, defined by the programmer,
and attached to these events are commands that are executed each
time the event "happens"


The latest version of Gui4Cli can be found on aminet/dev/gui/gui4cli.lha

@endnode

